econet-eth: WHNAT TX probe -- Phase 0 fail-fast for WiFi HW-NAT

The WiFi HW-NAT port (replicating the OEM WHNAT scheme) hinges on one
irreducible hardware unknown: can our QDMA, given the OEM WiFi TX msg
(raw[0]=0x38 = channel 7/queue 0, raw[1]=0x200000 = WiFi fport, bit 21),
inject a frame into the PCIe-attached MT7603 so it transmits over the air?
This adds a minimal, self-contained probe to settle that before building any
infrastructure.

en75_whnat_tx_probe() builds a synthetic broadcast or directed frame with a
"WHNATPROBE" marker, optionally inserts the WiFi mux VLAN tag, and posts it to
qdma[0] (the GDM1/conduit ring the OEM wifi_fast uses) with the WiFi msg. Knobs
are exposed as runtime-writable module params, so the whole test matrix sweeps
without a reload:

  whnat_tx_vid / tag / msg0 / msg1 / da_hi / da_lo, then:
  echo 1 > .../whnat_tx_fire

whnat_tx_imm was kept as a knob during early bring-up, but must not be used as a
normal probe path: live F0 testing on the XR500v showed that setting
TX_IMMEDIATE_DONE globally and firing the WiFi descriptor can wedge/reboot the
device. Observe with a monitor sniffer on the AP channel (the AP must be
wifi-up). Nothing here touches the PPE/NAT datapath; it is a diagnostic, dropped
once the path is productized.

The probe skb is attached to qdma->napi_dev, and TX completion skips BQL
accounting for that dummy netdev. Descriptors that complete through the normal
TX done queue can then be freed without tripping BQL's completion sanity check.
